00029 // Datagram encoding
00030 #define LPROTOCOL_DATAGRAM_ENCODING_SHORT_EQUALDATAFIELDSSIZE                   2
00031 // Designed to encode sequences of the same data type, which can be char, int, float as well as structs.
00032 // Format: HEADER + FUNCTION + DATAGRAMSIZE + DATASIZE + DATA_1 + ... + DATA_N + CHECKSUM
00033 // HEADER: unsigned char (byte), given by LPROTOCOL_DATAGRAM_HEADER
00034 // FUNCTION: unsigned char (byte), representing the procedure to be applied to data
00035 // DATAGRAMSIZE: unsigned char (byte), representing the total datagram size in bytes. If DATAGRAMSIZE == 4, means no data.
00036 // DATASIZE: unsigned char (byte), representing the number of bytes of each data. 
00037 // DATA_1: sequence of unsigned char (1 byte), representing the data indexed 1
00038 // DATA_N: sequence of unsigned char (1 byte), representing the data indexed N
00039 // CHECKSUM: unsigned char (byte), given by the sum of all bytes of the datagram
00040 // N is obtained from N = (DATAGRAMSIZE - 4)/DATASIZE
00041 // If each data has always the same number of bytes given by EACHDATASIZE, to be known at sender as well as at the receiver, 
00042 // Designed to encode sequences of the same data type, which can be char, int, float as well as structs.

00059 #define LPROTOCOL_DATAGRAM_ENCODING_LONG                                                                4
00060 // Designed to encode very long sequences of one data, usualy a struct.
00061 // Format: HEADER + FUNCTION + DATAGRAMSIZE_BYTE_4 + DATAGRAMSIZE_BYTE_3 + DATAGRAMSIZE_BYTE_2 + DATAGRAMSIZE_BYTE_1  + DATA + CHECKSUM
00062 // HEADER: unsigned char (byte), given by LPROTOCOL_DATAGRAM_HEADER
00063 // FUNCTION: unsigned char (byte), representing the procedure to be applied to data
00064 // DATAGRAMSIZE_BYTE_4: unsigned char (byte), to obtain the datagram size.
00065 // DATAGRAMSIZE_BYTE_3: unsigned char (byte), to obtain the datagram size.
00066 // DATAGRAMSIZE_BYTE_2: unsigned char (byte), to obtain the datagram size.
00067 // DATAGRAMSIZE_BYTE_1: unsigned char (byte), to obtain the datagram size. 
00068 //    DATAGRAMSIZE is given by DATAGRAMSIZE_BYTE_3*(1 << 24) + DATAGRAMSIZE_BYTE_3*(1 << 16) + DATAGRAMSIZE_BYTE_2*(1 << 8) + DATAGRAMSIZE_BYTE_1
00069 //    DATAGRAMSIZE == 7, means no data.
00070 // DATASIZE_1: unsigned char (byte), representing the number of bytes of DATA_1. 
00071 // DATA_1: sequence of unsigned char (1 byte), representing the data indexed 1
